    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, I'd be happy to help you with that. A confidentiality period in a contract is a time frame during which the parties involved agree not to share certain information. It's like a secret pact between two friends, where they promise not to tell anyone about their private plans for a while. Imagine you're sharing a secret with a friend, and you both agree to keep it under wraps for a certain number of days. That's essentially what a confidentiality period is.\n\nOn the other hand, a survival clause is a bit like a protective spell that keeps a certain part of the contract alive even after the rest of the agreement has ended. It's like having a magical shield that ensures a specific agreement or condition remains in place, even if the rest of the contract is no longer relevant. Imagine you're playing a game with your friends, and there's a rule that says if you win, you get to keep a special toy forever. That's the essence of a survival clause.\n\nSo, in summary, a confidentiality period is about keeping secrets for a certain time, while a survival clause is about keeping certain parts of the contract alive even after the rest has ended. I hope that helps you understand the difference!",
      "source": "target",
